# Gluestack UI Components

Use `@gluestack-ui/themed` components instead of raw React Native primitives. This ensures consistent theming, dark mode support, and accessibility across the app.

## Component Mapping

| Instead of (RN)             | Use (Gluestack)                                    |
|-----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
| `<Text>`                    | `<Text>` from `@gluestack-ui/themed`                |
| `<TextInput>`               | `<Input>` + `<InputField>`                          |
| `<TouchableOpacity>`        | `<Button>` + `<ButtonText>` / `<Pressable>`         |
| `<View>` (semantic)         | `<Box>`, `<HStack>`, `<VStack>`, `<Center>`         |
| `<Switch>`                  | `<Switch>` from `@gluestack-ui/themed`              |
| `<Modal>`                   | `<Modal>` + `<ModalBackdrop>` + `<ModalContent>`    |
| `<Alert>`                   | `<Alert>` + `<AlertIcon>` + `<AlertText>`           |
| `<ActivityIndicator>`       | `<Spinner>`                                         |
| `<Image>`                   | `<Image>` from `@gluestack-ui/themed`               |
| `<FlatList>` item wrappers  | `<Box>` or `<Pressable>` (FlatList itself stays RN) |

## When Raw RN is OK

- `<View>` for pure layout containers with no semantic meaning (flex wrappers)
- `<FlatList>`, `<SectionList>`, `<ScrollView>` — no Gluestack equivalents
- `<StatusBar>`, `<KeyboardAvoidingView>`, `<SafeAreaView>` — system primitives
- `<Animated.View>` — Reanimated animation wrappers

## Examples

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — raw RN primitives for interactive/semantic UI
import { Text, TextInput, TouchableOpacity } from 'react-native';
<TouchableOpacity onPress={onSave}>
  <Text>Save</Text>
</TouchableOpacity>
<TextInput value={name} onChangeText={setName} />

// ✅ GOOD — Gluestack components
import { Button, ButtonText, Input, InputField } from '@gluestack-ui/themed';
<Button onPress={onSave}>
  <ButtonText>{t('common.save')}</ButtonText>
</Button>
<Input>
  <InputField value={name} onChangeText={setName} />
</Input>
```

## Composition Pattern

Gluestack uses compound components. Always import the sub-parts:

```tsx
import {
  Modal,
  ModalBackdrop,
  ModalContent,
  ModalHeader,
  ModalBody,
  ModalFooter,
  ModalCloseButton,
} from '@gluestack-ui/themed';
```

## Styling

Gluestack components accept NativeWind `className` plus Gluestack props (`size`, `variant`, `action`). Prefer Gluestack semantic props for variants, NativeWind for layout:

```tsx
<Button size="lg" variant="solid" action="primary" className="mt-md">
  <ButtonText>{t('common.continue')}</ButtonText>
</Button>
```
